Introduction

This assignment focuses on the analysis and prediction of the age of abalone, a type of marine mollusk, using physical measurements. Throughout this assignment, students will explore various linear and non-linear regression techniques, evaluate model performance, and consider the implications of multicollinearity and model selection criteria.

Learning Outcomes

By the end of this assignment, students will be able to:

  • Identify the type of problem (classification, regression, supervised, unsupervised) presented by the abalone dataset.
  • Load and preprocess data in R, ensuring appropriate data types for each variable.
  • Visualize data distributions and assess assumptions of the linear model using plots such as histograms and boxplots.
  • Split data into training and testing sets and fit simple and multiple linear regression models to the training set.
  • Evaluate model performance using metrics such as R-squared, Adjusted R-squared, and Mean Squared Error (MSE).
  • Extend linear models by incorporating polynomial terms and categorical predictors, and assess their impact on model performance.
  • Investigate multicollinearity using correlation matrices
  • Implement forward selection to choose additional predictors for the regression model.
  • Compare the predictive performance of different models and make informed decisions on model selection.
  • Explore the use of K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) regression and understand the bias-variance tradeoff in this context.
  • Justify the choice of model based on diagnostic plots and model evaluation criteria.

Abalone

The abalone dataset, available from the UCI Machine Learning Repository, contains data related to physical measurements of abalones, a type of marine mollusk. Determining the age of an abalone traditionally involves cutting through the shell, staining it, and counting the number of rings under a microscope. In this portion of the assignment we seek aim to predict the age of abalone from physical measurements.

Related material: Lab 1 and Lab 2; Lectures 3, 4, and 5

hist(abalone$Rings)

The distribution is skewed right. This does not violate any assumption of the linear model because the normality assumptions is on the residuals, not on the response variable \(y\).

Exercise 8 (Checking Assumptions) (1 point) Based on the scatter plot produced in the previous question, do the assumptions of linearity and homoscedasticity model appear to be satisfied? Justify your answer.

Linearity: Based on the scatterplot, the relation does appear to be a (weak) linear relationship between Rings and Length.

Homoscedasticity: There appears to be more spread in the Rings variable as Length increases, especially between Length values of 0.4 and 0.6. This suggests that the variance of the residuals is not constant, which violates the homoscedasticity assumption.

Exercise 9 (Normality of Residuals) (1 point) Run some diagnostic checks to investigate whether or not the normality of residuals assumption is reasonable.

We can check the first two plots of the following:

par(mfrow=c(2,2)) # sets up a 2x2 plotting layout,
plot(lm_length)

Based on the Q-Q plot there appears to be a clear violation of the normality assumption on the residuals.

Tip

Aside: note that you can access the residual plot directly using:

plot(lm_length, which = 2)

Multiple Linear Regression

Exercise 10 (Polynomial Regression) (1 point) Fit a polynomial regression model of degree 2 for Length (i.e., include Length^2 as an additional predictor). Assess the significance of the quadratic term by examining the \(p\)-values, the adjusted R-squared value, and diagnostic plots for any potential violations of linear model assumptions.

lm_poly <- lm(Rings ~ Length + I(Length^2), data = train_data)
summary(lm_poly)

Call:
lm(formula = Rings ~ Length + I(Length^2), data = train_data)

Residuals:
    Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
-5.2152 -1.6535 -0.6723  0.7908 16.9653 

Coefficients:
            Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)

I(Length^2) -12.9073     3.0539  -4.226 2.48e-05 ***

Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Residual standard error: 2.605 on 2085 degrees of freedom
Multiple R-squared:  0.3228,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.3221 
F-statistic: 496.9 on 2 and 2085 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

p-value of I(Length^2): The \(p\)-value for the quadratic term I(Length^2) is 2.4765479^{-5} which is much less than 0.05. This indicates that the quadratic term is statistically significant in the model.

Adjusted R-squared: The adjusted R-squared value is 0.3221465 . While this shows a modest increase from typical simple linear regression models, it suggests that the quadratic term has improved the model’s fit, but the overall variance explained by the model is still relatively low.

Although the polynomial term is significant and leads to a small increase in adjusted R-squared, the model still seems to violate the model assumptions.

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(lm_poly)

Namely:

  • Residuals vs. Fitted: There is some pattern in the residuals, indicating potential non-linearity or other issues. The residuals are not evenly spread around the zero line, suggesting that the model might still not be fully capturing the relationship.

  • Q-Q Plot: The residuals deviate from the theoretical quantiles, especially at the tails, indicating potential issues with normality.

  • Scale-Location: There is a visible pattern in the plot, which may indicate non-constant variance (heteroscedasticity).

Exercise 12 (Parallel lines model) (2 points) Write down the equation of the line for each level of Sex based on the model from Exercise 11

\[ \begin{align} \texttt{Rings} = \begin{cases} \phantom{\hat \beta_0 + \hat \beta_1 \texttt{Length} + \hat \beta_2 \texttt{SexI} + \hat \beta_3 \texttt{SexM}}\dots & \text{if Female} \\ \phantom{\hat \beta_0 + \hat \beta_1 \texttt{Length}+ \hat \beta_2 \texttt{SexI} + \hat \beta_3 \texttt{SexM}}\dots & \text{if Male} \\ \phantom{\hat \beta_0 + \hat \beta_1 \texttt{Length}+ \hat \beta_2 \texttt{SexI} + \hat \beta_3 \texttt{SexM}}\dots & \text{if Infant} \end{cases} \end{align} \]

\[ \begin{align} \texttt{Rings} &= \begin{cases} {\hat \beta_0 + \hat \beta_1 \texttt{Length}+ \hat \beta_2 \texttt{SexI} + \hat \beta_3 \texttt{SexM}} & \text{if Female} \\ {\hat \beta_0 + \hat \beta_1 \texttt{Length}+ \hat \beta_2 \texttt{SexI} + \hat \beta_3 \texttt{SexM}} & \text{if Male} \\ {\hat \beta_0 + \hat \beta_1 \texttt{Length}+ \hat \beta_2 \texttt{SexI} + \hat \beta_3 \texttt{SexM}} & \text{if Infant} \end{cases}\\ \phantom{\texttt{Rings}} \\ &= \begin{cases} { 4.108 + 11.976 \cdot \texttt{Length}+ (-1.434) \times 0 + (-0.273)\times 0} & \text{if Female} \\ { 4.108 + 11.976\cdot \texttt{Length}+ (-1.434 )\times 0 + (-0.273) \times 1} & \text{if Male} \\ { 4.108 + 11.976\cdot \texttt{Length}+ (-1.434) \times 1 + (-0.273) \times 0} & \text{if Infant} \end{cases}\\ \phantom{\texttt{Rings}} \\ &= \begin{cases} { 4.108 + 11.976 \cdot \texttt{Length}} & \text{if Female} \\ { 4.108 + 11.976\cdot \texttt{Length} + (-0.273) \times 1} & \text{if Male} \\ { 4.108 + 11.976\cdot \texttt{Length}+ (-1.434) \times 1} & \text{if Infant} \end{cases}\\ \phantom{\texttt{Rings}} \\ &= \begin{cases} { 4.108 + 11.976 \cdot \texttt{Length}} & \text{if Female} \\ { 3.835 + 11.976\cdot \texttt{Length} } & \text{if Male} \\ { 2.674 + 11.976\cdot \texttt{Length}} & \text{if Infant} \end{cases} \end{align} \]

Exercise 13 (Reference level) (0.5 point) What is the reference level for the model fitted in Exercise 11?

  1. Female
  2. Male
  3. Infant
  4. There is not enough information to say

The reference level will be the first level of the categorical variable. For me, the reference level is F (female). Depending on how they coded up Sex their reference level could possibly be I (infant) or M (male).

Tip

To identify the reference level from the R output, you can look at the coefficients of the other levels. The reference level is the one that does not appear in the output as a coefficient.

Exercise 15 (Forward selection - one step) (1 point) Beginning with the model from Exercise 11, use forward selection to select a single additional predictor.

Warning

TA markers note: there will be variation in this answer. The key is that they need to fit 6 models (one for each option they have for predictors) and select the model that has the best improvement to the model fit. They may use either \(p\)-values of R-squared values to access this. Astute students may even go so far as to assess this based on the AIC (which was in the supplementary reading but not in the main lecture).

With Length and Sex already being used as predictors we have Diameter, Height, WholeWeight,ShuckedWeight, VisceraWeight, and ShellWeight to choose from. To select we need to fit the 7 models and select the one with the add the variable that results in the best improvement to the model fit.

Note

As done in labs, I will select the one with the smallest \(p\)-value but you could alternatively use the one that increase the R-squared value the most or improves the AIC (not discussed in lecture or lab).

pvals <- c(

  summary(lm_length_sex_height)$coefficients[5,4], 
  summary(lm_length_sex_wweight)$coefficients[5,4],

  summary(lm_length_sex_vweight)$coefficients[5,4], 
  summary(lm_length_sex_shweight)$coefficients[5,4]
)

which.max(pvals)
[1] 5

In my case, option 5, i.e. the inclusion of VisceraWeight would be selected.

Alternatively, students may opt to include the predictor that shows the greatest improvement on the R-squared value. In that case, option 6, the model including ShellWeight would be the optimal choice.

As indicated by the large (close to 1) values, there is high amounts of correlation between predictor variables. In the provided correlation matrix, the pair of predictor variables with the highest correlation is Length and Diameter.

Aside (not needed for full marks): Many of the predictors have a high correlation, eg, WholeWeight and ShuckedWeight are highly correlated with with a correlation coefficient of approximately 0.97.

Implication: High correlation between predictor variables can lead to multicollinearity, which makes it difficult to isolate the individual effect of each predictor on the response variable. This can cause unstable estimates for the regression coefficients and increase the standard errors, leading to less reliable hypothesis tests. We should keep this in mind moving into the next section.

Aside (not for marks): Since it is cumbersome to look at a bunch of numbers in a matrix, you could alternatively look at a heatmap. Heatmaps provide a clear visual representation of the strength and direction of relationships between variables.

Exercise 23 (1 point) What would you recommend as the best choice from the set of models summarized in Exercise 22. Justify your answer.

KNN Regression

The plot in Figure 4 plots the Mean Squared Error (MSE) on the test set for a K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) regression model with varying values of \(k\) (10, 50, 100, 200, 300).

Code 
library(caret)
knn_mse_test = NULL

for (k in c(10, 50, 100, 200, 300)){
  kmod <- knnreg(Rings ~ Length, data = train_data, k = k)
  yhat = predict(kmod, test_data)
  knn_mse_test[k] = mean((test_data$Rings - yhat)^2)
}

plot(knn_mse_test, type = "b", ylab = "MSE test", xlab = "k", main = "KNN regression")

Exercise 24 (Bias-Variance Tradeoff:) (1 point) Explain how the changes in test MSE across different values of \(k\) illustrate the bias-variance tradeoff in the context of KNN regression.

  • Low \(k\) Values \(\implies\) high variance (0.5 point) : The model is capturing too much noise in the training data and thus does not generalize well to the test data. With fewer neighbors, the model is highly sensitive to small changes in the data, which leads to poor performance on unseen data (high variance).
  • High \(k\) Values \(\implies\) low variance (0.5 point):

Exercise 25 (Model Performance) (1 point) : What does a relatively high test MSE at low values of \(k = 10\) indicate about the model’s performance in terms of overfitting or underfitting?

  • Low \(k\) Values \(\implies\) overfitting (0.5 point) : For lower values of \(k\) (e.g., \(k = 10\)), the model is more flexible, which can lead to high variance and overfitting. This is indicated by relatively high test MSE values at \(k = 10\).

  • High \(k\) Values \(\implies\) underfitting (0.5 point) : As \(k\) increases, the model becomes less flexible, reducing variance but increasing bias. Very high values, like \(k = 300\), result in higher MSE due to underfitting.

Exercise 26 (Recommendations) (1 point) Based on the observed MSE values, what would you recommend as the best choice for \(k\)? Justify your answer.

Based on the plot, \(k=100\) is recommended because it minimizes the test MSE. In other words, it strikes a balance where the variance is reduced without adding too much bias, indicating the tradeoff is minimized. The model is neither too complex (avoiding overfitting) nor too simple (avoiding underfitting), making it a suitable choice for generalization.
